---

<BaseLayout title="3-6 Months: Baby Development, Sleep & Feeding" description="Months 3–6 development data: rolling, laughing, the 4-month sleep regression, and feeding schedules for breastfed and formula-fed babies." schema={schema} faqSchema={faqSchema} pageType="Article">
  <article class="article">
    <header class="article-header">
      <h1>3–6 Month Baby Development: Rolling, Laughing & the 4-Month Sleep Shift</h1>
      <p class="article-meta">Ages 3–6 months · Updated March 2026</p>
    </header>

    <div class="topic-nav">
      <a href="/ages/3-6-months/">Overview</a>
      <a href="/ages/3-6-months/milestones/">Milestones</a>
      <a href="/ages/3-6-months/sleep/">Sleep</a>
      <a href="/ages/3-6-months/feeding/">Feeding</a>
    </div>

    <div class="article-content">
      <p>Months 3–6 mark the transition from newborn to infant. Crying decreases, sleep begins consolidating (with one significant disruption at 4 months), and your baby becomes a genuinely interactive social creature. First laughs, rolling, and intentional reaching all land in this window.</p>

      <h2>Physical Development</h2>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Head control:</strong> Steady, no head lag when pulled to sitting by 4 months</li>
        <li><strong>Rolling:</strong> Front-to-back by 3–5 months; back-to-front by 4–6 months</li>
        <li><strong>Supported sitting:</strong> Sits with support for short periods by 4–5 months; tripod sit emerging by 6 months</li>
        <li><strong>Reaching:</strong> Intentional reaching and batting at objects from about 3–4 months</li>
        <li><strong>Grasp:</strong> Palmar grasp — uses whole hand to grab objects; transfers between hands beginning around 5–6 months</li>
        <li><strong>Bearing weight:</strong> Pushes down with legs when held upright on a surface</li>
        <li><strong>Tummy time progress:</strong> Mini push-up by 3–4 months; extended arm push-up by 5–6 months</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Cognitive Development</h2>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Object permanence:</strong> Early signs — looks for a dropped toy at 5–6 months</li>
        <li><strong>Cause and effect:</strong> Repeats actions to reproduce interesting results (shaking a rattle)</li>
        <li><strong>Visual acuity:</strong> Near-adult color vision and depth perception by ~4 months</li>
        <li><strong>Attention span:</strong> Can focus on an interesting object or face for several minutes</li>
        <li><strong>Imitation:</strong> Begins imitating facial expressions and simple sounds</li>
        <li><strong>Exploration:</strong> Everything goes to the mouth — oral exploration is how infants process sensory data</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Social & Language Development</h2>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Laughter:</strong> Full belly laughs typically emerge at 3–4 months</li>
        <li><strong>Vocalization:</strong> Babbling with consonant-vowel combinations ("ba," "da," "ga") starts around 4–5 months</li>
        <li><strong>Reciprocal communication:</strong> Responds to your vocalizations, pauses, and waits for your response</li>
        <li><strong>Social referencing:</strong> Looks to caregiver faces to gauge reactions to new stimuli</li>
        <li><strong>Stranger awareness:</strong> Beginning to prefer familiar faces; early stranger wariness by 5–6 months</li>
        <li><strong>Emotion recognition:</strong> Distinguishes happy, sad, and angry facial expressions</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Sleep Patterns</h2>
      <p>Sleep consolidates — then hits a structural shift at 4 months:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Total sleep:</strong> 12–16 hours per 24 hours</li>
        <li><strong>Night sleep:</strong> Many babies achieve 5–6+ hour stretches by 3–4 months</li>
        <li><strong>4-month sleep regression:</strong> Sleep architecture permanently matures around 4 months; night waking increases until baby learns to link sleep cycles independently</li>
        <li><strong>Naps:</strong> 3 naps per day, transitioning to 2 longer naps by ~6 months</li>
        <li><strong>Wake windows:</strong> 1.5–2 hours between sleep periods</li>
        <li><strong>Sleep training readiness:</strong> Most experts recommend waiting until at least 4 months (adjusted age) before formal sleep training</li>
        <li><strong>Safe sleep:</strong> Back to sleep on firm flat surface; no change to safe sleep guidelines at this age</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Feeding Schedule & Amounts</h2>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Breastfed frequency:</strong> 5–7 times per 24 hours; feeding sessions become faster and more efficient</li>
        <li><strong>Formula frequency:</strong> 5–6 times per 24 hours</li>
        <li><strong>Formula amount:</strong> 4–6 oz per feeding, totaling ~24–36 oz/day</li>
        <li><strong>Growth spurts:</strong> Expect increased hunger around 3 months, 4 months, and 6 months</li>
        <li><strong>Solid food:</strong> Not recommended before 4 months; AAP recommends waiting until 6 months unless pediatrician advises otherwise</li>
        <li><strong>Readiness for solids (not a schedule, a checklist):</strong> Sits with minimal support, good head control, tongue-thrust reflex gone, interest in food, doubles birth weight</li>
        <li><strong>Distractible feeding:</strong> Babies become easily distracted during feeds at this age — quiet environments help</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Teething</h2>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Typical onset:</strong> 4–7 months, but wide variation (some babies tooth at 3 months, some at 12+)</li>
        <li><strong>First teeth:</strong> Lower central incisors usually erupt first</li>
        <li><strong>Symptoms:</strong> Drooling, chewing, fussiness, mild gum swelling</li>
        <li><strong>Drooling:</strong> Heavy drool from 2–4 months onward is typically salivary gland maturation, not teething</li>
        <li><strong>Relief:</strong> Chilled (not frozen) teething rings, firm rubber teethers, gum massage</li>
        <li><strong>Avoid:</strong> Teething tablets with belladonna, benzocaine gels, amber necklaces (CPSC hazard)</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Sensory & Environmental Stimulation</h2>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>High-contrast visuals:</strong> Less critical now — full color vision is established</li>
        <li><strong>Mirrors:</strong> Babies are fascinated by their own reflection; safe unbreakable mirrors are excellent toys</li>
        <li><strong>Texture exploration:</strong> Offer varied surfaces to touch and mouth (soft, bumpy, smooth)</li>
        <li><strong>Outdoor time:</strong> Novel environments, sounds, and visual complexity are stimulating</li>
        <li><strong>Reading:</strong> Even at this age, hearing language-rich reading builds vocabulary and phonemic awareness</li>
        <li><strong>Screen time:</strong> AAP recommends no screens (except video chat) under 18–24 months</li>
      </ul>

      <div class="faq-section">
        <h2>Common Questions</h2>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <p class="faq-question">My 4-month-old was sleeping well and now wakes every hour. What happened?</p>
          <p class="faq-answer">This is the 4-month sleep regression — a permanent neurological change in sleep architecture. Babies who needed feeding or rocking to fall asleep now need the same thing between every sleep cycle (every 45–60 min). The solution isn't waiting it out; it's helping baby learn to fall asleep independently at the start of the night.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <p class="faq-question">My 5-month-old isn't rolling yet. Should I be concerned?</p>
          <p class="faq-answer">Not necessarily. Rolling typically appears between 3–6 months, and babies with less tummy time often roll later. If your baby has good head control, reaches for objects, and shows normal muscle tone, limited rolling is often a tummy-time issue, not a developmental one. Mention it at your 6-month visit if not rolling by then.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <p class="faq-question">Can I give my 5-month-old water?</p>
          <p class="faq-answer">No. Infants under 6 months get all fluid from breast milk or formula. Adding water can dilute sodium levels and cause hyponatremia (a dangerous electrolyte imbalance). After 6 months and with solids introduction, small amounts of water are fine.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <p class="faq-question">My 4-month-old fights every nap. Is this normal?</p>
          <p class="faq-answer">Very common. Nap development lags behind night sleep maturation. Short, fragmented naps — often 30–45 minutes — are typical at 4 months. Longer, more consolidated naps usually develop between 5–6 months. Consistent pre-nap routines and watching wake windows help.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <p class="faq-question">Is it safe to use a sleep sack at 4 months?</p>
          <p class="faq-answer">Yes — sleep sacks (wearable blankets) are safe and recommended. They replace loose blankets (a SIDS risk) and keep the baby appropriately warm. Once baby shows signs of rolling, transition from swaddle to arms-free sleep sack.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="red-flags">
        <h3>When to Contact Your Pediatrician</h3>
        <ul>
          <li>No social smile by 3 months</li>
          <li>No laughing or squealing by 4–5 months</li>
          <li>Doesn't reach for or grasp objects by 4–5 months</li>
          <li>Poor head control — still significant head lag at 4 months</li>
          <li>Doesn't roll either direction by 6 months</li>
          <li>Doesn't babble ("ba," "da," "ga") by 6 months</li>
          <li>Doesn't respond to sounds or voices</li>
          <li>Seems very stiff or very floppy</li>
          <li>Poor weight gain or weight loss</li>
          <li>Feeding refusal lasting more than a day</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>
  </article>
</BaseLayout>
